<paragraph id="C06536BE9B37FFB068992D1C5627C616" blockId="10.[189,1399,1819,2025]" lastBlockId="11.[189,1399,265,327]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Disc diameter 
<quantity id="07229B5B9B37FFB1694B2D1C56B6C064" box="[367,452,1819,1845]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="mm" value="11.0">11 mm</quantity>
and collected attached to a gorgonian species. Our specimen is similar to the 
<typeStatus id="1F61881C9B37FFB168992D395656C009" box="[189,292,1854,1880]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">holotype</typeStatus>
description by 
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B37FFB169C92D395443C009" author="Muller J. &amp; Troschel F. H." box="[493,817,1854,1880]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refId="ref39511" refString="Muller J. &amp; Troschel F. H. 1842. System der Asteriden. 1. Asteriae. 2. Ophiuridae. Vieweg, Braunschweig, Germany." type="book" year="1842">Müller &amp; Troschel (1842)</bibRefCitation>
and later published descriptions (
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B37FFB16CFA2D395200C009" author="Baker A. N." box="[1246,1394,1854,1880]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="11 - 83" refId="ref36367" refString="Baker A. N. 1980. Euryalinid Ophiuroidea (Echinodermata) from Australia, New Zealand, and the South-west Pacific Ocean. New Zealand Journal of Zoology 7 (1): 11 - 83. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03014223.1980.10423763" type="journal article" year="1980">Baker 1980</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B37FFB168992D66560FC02A" author="McKnight D. G." box="[189,381,1889,1915]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 79" refId="ref39415" refString="McKnight D. G. 2000. The marine fauna of New Zealand: basket-stars and snake-stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea: Euryalinida). NIWA Biodiversity Memoir 115: 1 - 79." type="journal article" year="2000">McKnight 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B37FFB169A82D665514C02A" author="Olbers J. M. &amp; Griffiths C. L. &amp; O'Hara T. D. &amp; Samyn Y." box="[396,614,1889,1915]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" pagination="1 - 354" refId="ref40677" refString="Olbers J. M., Griffiths C. L., O'Hara T. D. &amp; Samyn Y. 2019. Field guide to the brittle and basket stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) of South Africa. Abc Taxa 19: 1 - 354. Available from http: // www. abctaxa. be / volumes / volume _ 19 _ fieldguide-brittle-and-basket-stars [accessed 16 Feb. 2022]." type="journal article" year="2019">
Olbers 
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B37FFB169C12D655551C02A" box="[485,547,1889,1915]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation id="58E12A3B9B37FFB16AA42D6655B8C02A" box="[640,714,1889,1915]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,478,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-112@11.[189,1397,478,1909]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 2. Asteronyx loveni Müller &amp; Troschel, 1842 (IDSSE EEB-SW0002). A. Dorsal disc. B. Ventral disc. C. Oral frame. D. Genital slit. E. Dorsal arm. F. Arm spines. Abbreviations: ars = arm spines; gs = genital slit; rs = radial shield; tp = tentacle pore. Scale bars: A–B = 2 mm; C–E = 1 mm; F = 200 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6419526" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6419526/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Vertebrae with a streptospondylous articulation and the lateral arm plate bears four to five spine articulations, which lack a separate nerve opening (
<figureCitation id="58E12A3B9B37FFB16D3A2D8F5215C0F3" box="[1310,1383,1928,1954]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[189,232,1858,1884]" captionTargetBox="[206,1382,265,1832]" captionTargetId="figure-99@12.[206,1382,265,1832]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 3. Asteronyx loveni Müller &amp; Troschel, 1842, SEM (IDSSE EEB-SW0002).A–B. Lateral arm plates (external, internal). C–G. Vertebrae. C. Proximal view. D. Distal view. E. Ventral view. F. Dorsal view. G. Lateral view. Abbreviations: asa = arm spine articulation; D = dorsal; Dist = distal; mo = muscle opening; p = perforation of inner side; Prox = proximal; V = ventral. Scale bars: A–B = 300 µm; C–D, F–G = 500 µm; E = 800 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6419530" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6419530/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Species of 
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B37FFB169652DAC56C7C094" authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1842" box="[321,437,1963,1989]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Asteronychidae" genus="Asteronyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Euryalida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B37FFB169652DAC56C7C094" box="[321,437,1963,1989]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Asteronyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are usually found on mud and sand, associated with gorgonians and pennatulids. In 1959 and from 1976 to 1981, 
<specimenCount id="D6DCFD379B37FFB16A102DC955A0C0B9" box="[564,722,1998,2025]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="generic">52 specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B37FFB16AD12DC9542EC0B9" authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1842" box="[757,860,1998,2024]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Asteronychidae" genus="Asteronyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Euryalida" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="loveni">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B37FFB16AD12DC9542EC0B9" box="[757,860,1998,2024]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">A. loveni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected from the East and South 
<collectingCountry id="B8CD762E9B37FFB16D142DC95204C0B9" box="[1328,1398,1998,2024]" name="China" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">China</collectingCountry>
seas, at depths of 
<quantity id="07229B5B9B36FFB069AA2B0E5551C675" box="[398,547,265,292]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.05" metricValueMax="11.0" metricValueMin="5.1" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="m" value="805.0" valueMax="1100.0" valueMin="510.0">510–1100 m</quantity>
. 
<taxonomicName id="07DA4D3D9B36FFB06A0B2B0E5581C672" authorityName="Muller &amp; Troschel" authorityYear="1842" box="[559,755,265,291]" class="Ophiuroidea" family="Asteronychidae" genus="Asteronyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Euryalida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="loveni">
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B36FFB06A0B2B0E5581C672" box="[559,755,265,291]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Asteronyx loveni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was first reported from the South 
<collectingCountry id="B8CD762E9B36FFB06CA12B0E53B9C672" box="[1157,1227,265,291]" name="China" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">China</collectingCountry>
Sea by 
<bibRefCitation id="A44B4B4F9B36FFB06D0E2B0E5623C616" author="Chang F. Y. &amp; Liao Y. L. &amp; Wu B. L." pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="53 - 68" refId="ref36751" refString="Chang F. Y., Liao Y. L. &amp; Wu B. L. 1962. Euryaliae of the China Sea. Acta Zoologica Sinica 14: 53 - 68." type="journal article" year="1962">
Chang 
<emphasis id="F2AEEAAC9B36FFB068992B2A578AC617" box="[189,248,300,326]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
(1962)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
